    <section class="section">
      <h2>What you'll find here</h2>
      <ul class="gains-list">
        <li>The complete process of building a rule-based trading system with AI — from zero code to live account</li>
        <li>How real orders get made, and where the system broke down</li>
        <li>The reasoning behind every strategy decision — why that choice, not another</li>
        <li>How to debug a system that's running on real money</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Current Status</h2>
      <p>An RS (Relative Strength) filter was added. Any stock with excess return below -3% vs. the KOSPI200 ETF (20-day) is disqualified as a buy candidate. Remaining candidates are sorted by excess return and purchased strongest-first. Empty slots stay in cash when no strong candidates qualify.</p>
      <p>Currently running BUY_DRY_RUN=True — buy logic in simulation, sell logic stays live. Switching to full live after 2–3 trading days of validation. Current live account closing balance: ₩4,890,000.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>The Problem Being Solved</h2>
      <p>Can a non-coder build and operate a real automated trading system by collaborating with AI?</p>
      <p>The operator handles <strong>judgment</strong>. AI handles <strong>execution</strong>. The question is whether this division of roles holds up when real capital is on the line. ₩5M is the answer in progress.</p>
      <p>The goal is not profit. The goal is the experience of building a system where AI operates real capital — by hand, from scratch.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Structure and How It Works</h2>
      <p>Three roles. The operator (철부지) sets strategy direction and makes final calls. GPT (메타철부지) handles strategy design and research. Claude Code handles code analysis and modification. KIS API (Korea Investment Securities) executes orders on the live account.</p>
      <p>Buy decisions run through a rule engine. RSI, MA20 deviation, market regime (5-condition scoring), RS filter — candidates that pass all four conditions are sorted by strength and scanned 3 times per day (10:00 / 13:00 / 14:00). Sells are handled automatically: +6% take-profit or trailing stop (+4% activation / -2% from peak), -3% stop-loss.</p>
    </section>

